<section os="linux;osx" id="sec.itk_inst">
  <title id="title.itk_inst">Insight Toolkit (<acronym>ITK</acronym>)
  Installation</title>

  <section>
    <title>Introduction</title>

    <para>The <ulink url="http://www.itk.org">Insight Toolkit</ulink>
    (<acronym>ITK</acronym>) is an open-source software library for
    performing segmentation and registration.  When the
    <acronym>ITK</acronym> toolkit is present, and SCIRun is appropriately
    configured, <acronym>ITK</acronym> filters are encapsulated in SCIRun
    modules for use in SCIRun networks.  By default, SCIRun encapsulates a
    subset of <acronym>ITK</acronym> filters.</para>

    <para>SCIRun encapsulates <acronym>ITK</acronym> filters using
    <acronym>XML</acronym>-based  description files.  An
    <acronym>XSLT</acronym> processor generates code for SCIRun modules from
    the <acronym>XML</acronym> descriptions and <acronym>XSL</acronym>
    stylesheets.  Users may encapsulate additional filters by writing
    <acronym>XML</acronym> descriptions of them.  See the <ulink url="(%=
    doc.treeUrl(%Q{doc/User/Guide/usersguide/srug8.html}) %)">SCIRun Users
    Guide</ulink> for more information.</para>

    <note os="linux">
      <para>The SCIRun/Insight <acronym>RPM</acronym> distribution of SCIRun
      <emphasis>includes</emphasis> support for <acronym>ITK</acronym>.  The
      <acronym>RPM</acronym> distribution installs Insight libraries in
      /usr/local/lib/InsightTookit.  The instructions in sections <xref
      linkend="sec.obitk"/>, <xref linkend="sec.cmake"/>, and <xref
      linkend="sec.itk_configsr"/> apply only to a source code installation
      of SCIRun.</para>
    </note>

    <para os="linux">SCIRun's <acronym>ITK</acronym> support depends on
    the presence of Java JDK 1.2.2 or later.  Environment variable
    <envar>JAVA_HOME</envar> must contain the path to the java
    <quote>JDK</quote> directory. The JDK directory is typically
    <filename>/usr/java</filename>, <filename>/usr/java2</filename>,
    or
    <filename>/usr/java/jdk<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable></filename>.</para>

    <para os="linux">
      For an sh-type shell:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
JAVA_HOME=/usr/java
export JAVA_HOME
      </literallayout>
      for a csh-type shell:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
setenv JAVA_HOME /usr/java
      </literallayout>
    </para>

    <para os="linux">Environment variable <envar>PATH</envar> must contain the
    path to the <command>java</command> command.  <envar>PATH</envar>
    is set as follows:</para>
    <para>
      For an sh-type shell:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
PATH=$JAVA_HOME/bin:$PATH
      </literallayout>
      and for a csh-type shell:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
setenv PATH $JAVA_HOME/bin:$PATH
      </literallayout>
    </para>

  </section>

  <section id="sec.obitk">
    <title id="sec.title.obitk">Obtaining <acronym>ITK</acronym></title>

    <para>
      The Insight toolkit must be installed before building SCIRun.
      The Insight toolkit and its installation instructions are
      available on the <ulink
      url="http://www.itk.org"><acronym>ITK</acronym> web
      site</ulink>.  SCIRun supports <acronym>ITK</acronym> versions
      1.6, 1.8, and 1.10.
    </para>

    <note os="linux;osx">
      <para>
	<acronym>ITK</acronym> versions 1.6 and 1.8 are not compatible
	with GCC 3.4.  Use <acronym>ITK</acronym> 1.10 if compiling
	with GCC 3.4.
      </para>
    </note>

    <para>
      <acronym>ITK</acronym> installation requires CMake, an
      open-source, cross-platform build tool.  CMake can be obtained
      from the <ulink url="http://www.cmake.org">CMake web
      site</ulink>.
    </para>

    <note>
      <para>SCIRun's Insight package must also be downloaded to add support
      for ITK in SCIRun.  See <xref linkend="sec.sources"/>.</para>
    </note>

  </section>

  <section id="sec.cmake">
    <title id="sec.title.cmake">CMake Special Instructions</title>

    <para>CMake is a program that generates ITK's Makefiles.  CMake's
    configuration variables determine how ITK is built.  Command
    <command>ccmake</command> is used to configure CMake's variables.
    After starting <command>ccmake</command>, turn on its advanced
    mode by pressing key <keycap>t</keycap>, and then set the
    following CMake variables to the indicated values:</para>
    
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
	<term><varname>BUILD_SHARED_LIBS</varname></term>
	<listitem>
	  <para>Set the value of <varname>BUILD_SHARED_LIBS</varname>
	  to <userinput os="linux">ON</userinput><userinput
	  os="osx">OFF</userinput></para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
	<term><varname>BUILD_TESTING</varname></term>
	<listitem>
	  <para>Set the value of <varname>BUILD_TESTING</varname> to
	  <userinput>OFF</userinput></para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
	<term><varname>BUILD_EXAMPLES</varname></term>
	<listitem>
	  <para>Set the value of <varname>BUILD_EXAMPLES</varname> to
	  <userinput>OFF</userinput></para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
	<term><varname>ITK_USE_SYSTEM_PNG</varname></term>
	<listitem>
	  <para>If <acronym>PNG</acronym> support in the third party
	  Teem software has been enabled (<xref
	  linkend="sec.third_party_inst"/>) then CMake variable
	  <varname>ITK_USE_SYSTEM_PNG</varname> should be set to
	  <literal>ON</literal>, otherwise
	  <varname>ITK_USE_SYSTEM_PNG</varname> should be set to
	  <literal>OFF</literal>.  When
	  <varname>ITK_USE_SYSTEM_PNG</varname> is set to
	  <literal>ON</literal>, variables
	  <varname>PNG_LIBRARY</varname> and
	  <varname>PNG_PNG_INCLUDE_DIR</varname> may also need to be
	  set.</para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
	<term><varname>PNG_LIBRARY</varname></term>
	<listitem>
	  <para>Set <varname>PNG_LIBRARY</varname> to the absolute
	  pathname of the PNG library, for example, <filename
	  os="linux">/usr/local/lib/libpng.so</filename><filename
	  os="osx">/sw/lib/libpng.a</filename></para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
	<term><varname>PNG_PNG_INCLUDE_DIR</varname></term>
	<listitem>
	  <para>Set <varname>PNG_PNG_INCLUDE_DIR</varname> to the
	  absolute pathname of the directory containing PNG include
	  files, for example, <filename
	  os="linux">/usr/local/include</filename><filename
	  os="osx">/sw/include</filename></para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>

  </section>

  <section id="sec.itk_configsr">
    <title id="sec.title.itk_configsr">SCIRun Insight Configure Options</title>

    <para>The configure options below add support for Insight
    in SCIRun.  Include these options in the SCIRun
    <command>configure</command> command (see <xref linkend="sec.build-sr"
    />).
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
	<term><option>--with-insight=<replaceable>path-to-insight-libs</replaceable></option></term>
	<listitem>
	  <para>Specifies the directory containing the <acronym>ITK</acronym>
	  libraries.  The
	  ITK Software Guide refers to this directory as
	  ITK_BINARY_DIR.  The <acronym>ITK</acronym> library (or binary)
	  directory is commonly
	  <filename>/usr/local/lib/InsightToolkit</filename>.  The directory
	  will contain file <filename>ITKConfig.cmake</filename>.
	  </para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
    </para>
    <para>Here is an example SCIRun <command>configure</command> command:
    <literallayout class="monospaced">
../src/configure \
<phrase os="linux">--with-thirdparty=/usr/local/Thirdparty/1.8.0/Linux/gcc-3.2-32bit \</phrase>
<phrase os="osx">--with-thirdparty=/usr/local/Thirdparty_osx \</phrase>
--enable-package="BioPSE Teem Insight" \
--with-insight=/usr/local/lib/InsightToolkit
&#x22EE;
    </literallayout>
    Note that package Teem must be enabled.
    </para>

  </section>

</section>